BEGIN_PGML_HINT
Across a period on the periodic table, atomic size generally decreases from left to right. This happens because, as you move across a period, the number of protons in the nucleus increases, leading to a stronger positive charge. This stronger attraction pulls the electrons closer to the nucleus, resulting in a smaller atomic radius.

Down a group on the periodic table, atomic radius generally increases. This is because as you move down a group, the number of electron shells (energy levels) increases. More electron shells mean the outermost electrons are further away from the nucleus, resulting in a larger atomic radius. While the nuclear charge also increases down a group, the effect of added electron shells is more significant in determining the atomic radius.

